[
    {
        "content": "<p>Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> be an elementary topos with natural numbers object, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> the classifying topos over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> of an object, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msup><mi>X</mi><mo>∙</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X^\\bullet]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6741em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∙</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> the classifying topos over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> of a pointed object.  Are any of these true/well-known facts of topos theory?</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The morphism from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msup><mi>X</mi><mo>∙</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X^\\bullet]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6741em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∙</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> picking out the object part of the generic pointed object is an <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/etale%20geometric%20morphism\">[[etale geometric morphism]]</a> which is equivalent to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X]/X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> where X is the generic object.</li>\n<li>Any <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/etale%20geometric%20morphism\">[[etale geometric morphism]]</a> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E/E \\to \\mathcal E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span> over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> is a pullback of the above morphism along the geometric morphism classifying the object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span>.</li>\n<li>The global sections morphism of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> represents a stack on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> whenever <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> is such that it makes sense to ask if it represents a stack.</li>\n<li>Geometric morphisms that represent stacks are closed under precomposition by etale geometric morphisms, and whenever this makes sense, under precomposition by geometric morphisms that represent stacks.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Also are any of the equivalents in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-topos theory known?</p>",
        "id": 509732899,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743608528
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Evidence for the propositions above:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>A morphism into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msup><mi>X</mi><mo>∙</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X^\\bullet]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6741em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∙</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X]/X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is an object equipped with a global section, so they classify the same theory.</li>\n<li>A morphism into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E/E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span> is a whatever-<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span>-classifies with a constant of type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span>.  This is equivalent to a pointed object and a whatever-<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span>-classifies with the pointed object happening to be the same object that represents the sort <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span>.</li>\n<li>This one is just a feeling and I'm genuinely curious about it.</li>\n<li>Local homomorphisms of locales are closed under composition and geometric morphisms representing stacks are similar in nature.</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 509775739,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743621493
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Although it's not outright stated, I found enough proof in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2107.04417\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2107.04417</a> that <em>if</em> (3) is true then the represented stack is the canonical stack on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 509890613,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743673376
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>1 follows from the discussion in the other topic. One way of seeing 2 is actually as a special case of Diaconescu's theorem(!) The slice over X is equivalent the category of internal presheaves over X viewed as a discrete category, and Diaconescu's theorem says that this construction is pullback-stable in the way that you state.<br>\nFor the stack-based questions I don't even know the definition of stack in enough detail to figure out if they're plausible so I'll let someone else answer :)</p>",
        "id": 510032484,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1743712485
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What is a geometric morphism that represents a stack? Every geometric morphism canonically defines a topos-valued stack with respect to the canonical topology on the base. Is that what you're talking about?</p>",
        "id": 510064546,
        "sender_full_name": "Fernando Yamauti",
        "timestamp": 1743729213
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the paper I linked above they form a \"fundamental adjunction\" between stacks on a site <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\mathcal C,J)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> and essential, locally connected geometric morphisms over the topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Sh}(\\mathcal C,J)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Sh</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, specifically given by continuous comorphisms over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\mathcal C,J)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.  The left adjoint is given by Cartesian lifts in the fibration of the category of sites and comorphisms over the category of categories and functors.  The right adjoint is given by homming the image of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{EssTopos}/\\mathbf{Sh}(\\mathcal C,J)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">EssTopos</span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Sh</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> given by sheafifying the representables and slicing over them, the indexed version of what's called the \"canonical stack\", fiberwise into the argument, and taking the Grothendieck construction.  I think when your site is the canonical topology on a topos the canonical stack is the self-indexing.  This stack is not topos-valued; it's a different construction meant to represent all the small stacks (and it still gets some of the large ones like the canonical stack).</p>",
        "id": 510069441,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743732113
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm saying a geometric morphism \"represents a stack\" if it is the image of a stack under the left adjoint of the fundamental adjunction.</p>",
        "id": 510070967,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743733012
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What's the site in question 3?</p>",
        "id": 510071235,
        "sender_full_name": "Fernando Yamauti",
        "timestamp": 1743733180
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If I'm right it should work with any site that represents <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 510071395,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743733251
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So your base is not an elementary topos with NNO anymore?</p>",
        "id": 510071960,
        "sender_full_name": "Fernando Yamauti",
        "timestamp": 1743733523
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it probably would work with an internal site, like the trivial internal site, too, but the groundwork hasn't been done except for Grothendieck toposes and external sites, so it's probably best to stick with that for now.</p>",
        "id": 510072219,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743733653
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's an obvious geometric embedding of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo>→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S^\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6198em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, as the classifying topos over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> of a subterminal object, into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>.  The Yoneda embedding of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span> should factor into this and a geometric embedding of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> into presheaves on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo>→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S^\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6198em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>And the Grothendieck topology should be describable as \"a sieve covers iff it contains Cartesian lifts of all arrows in a jointly effective-epimorphic sieve\".</p>",
        "id": 510074293,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743735096
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see now what they mean. Their notation is a little nonstandard, but it seems they are talking about relative (or internal) presheaf topoi. So what you need to prove is that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{S}[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is a presheaf topos relative to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{S}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span>. The obvious candidate would be taking <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{S}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span>-presheaves over the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{S}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span>-cat given by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mrow><mi>f</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{S}_{fin}/(-)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0361em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3361em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.075em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">in</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, but I don't know if that works.</p>\n<p>It would be nice to have an external characterisation of what it means to be an internal presheaf topos without all the obscure blabbing about internal language.</p>",
        "id": 510076027,
        "sender_full_name": "Fernando Yamauti",
        "timestamp": 1743736280
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Wait, so is it that the image of the stacks under the left adjoint is the internal presheaf topoi as seen in Diaconescu's theorem?  I guess that would be true up to equivalence since every (small) stack is equivalent to (the externalization of) an internal category ...</p>",
        "id": 510077015,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743736891
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But wait, in that case how would it be possible to represent a large stack like the canonical stack?</p>",
        "id": 510077445,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743737191
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> represents any stack it's the canonical stack, since <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>Y</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≃</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Topos}/\\mathcal S(\\mathcal S/Y,\\mathcal S[X]) \\simeq \\mathcal S/Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Topos</span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">])</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≃</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> ...</p>",
        "id": 510077970,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743737633
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In any case <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>≃</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}[X] \\simeq \\mathbf{Set}^\\mathbf{FinSet}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≃</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9251em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9251em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.139em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbf mtight\">FinSet</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> but the stack on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> it represents (if any) is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> itself, not <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{FinSet}^\\mathsf{op}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7584em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">FinSet</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7584em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathsf mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 510079552,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743738566
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe this adjunction just isn't idempotent, unlike the other \"fundamental adjunction\"?  That would be more than a little bothersome.</p>",
        "id": 510081410,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743739721
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You're right. My suggestion can't possibly work. I was thinking, instead, about finite objects as an internal category, so my formula above is wrong. I confess I just skimmed through the paper quickly, but they seem to be repeating Giraud's construction on <a href=\"https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/BFb0073964\">\"Classifying Topos\"</a>.</p>",
        "id": 510081766,
        "sender_full_name": "Fernando Yamauti",
        "timestamp": 1743739990
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"438995\">James Deikun</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/On.20the.20classifying.20topos.20of.20an.20object/near/510077445\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But wait, in that case how would it be possible to represent a large stack like the canonical stack?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I don't think that change much. We can still consider the indexed version of presheaf topoi (see 2.2 in Giraud's paper). The left adjoint will still send the identity fibration to the identity geometric morphism.</p>\n<p>Looking back again, I think my suggestion was not wrong (apart from the lack of taking the opposite cat fiberwise).</p>",
        "id": 510088649,
        "sender_full_name": "Fernando Yamauti",
        "timestamp": 1743744110
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, I think I figured it out.  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> actually does represent the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>-stack <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{FinSet}^\\mathsf{op}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7584em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">FinSet</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7584em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathsf mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.  The text had led me to think otherwise, but they really do mean the slice category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{EssTopos}^\\mathsf{co}/\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0001em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">EssTopos</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7501em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.139em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathsf mtight\">co</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span>, with the morphisms also being essential.  You get away without this for sheaves because geometric morphisms are basically something similar to the Ind-completion of essential geometric morphisms (exactly the Ind-completion in the case of morphisms from stacks into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}[X]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>) and Ind-completion acts trivially on discrete categories.  This way everything makes sense, and the adjunction is idempotent, and the representing site for the canonical stack might be too big to present a topos but there are lots of smaller classifying objects for the small-enough sheaves.  I think (3) is still true and the process to prove it is what you said.</p>",
        "id": 510146415,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1743762646
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I look forward to understanding this discussion. In the mean time, out of curiosity, what motivated this question <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"438995\">@James Deikun</span> ?</p>",
        "id": 510194845,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1743771213
